{"answer": "The critic misreads the forbidden case. The case does not assert that the Amarna period caused permanent collapse; it states that the target’s mechanism—Egyptian absorption of cosmic disorder via the Osiris-Seth cycle—would be falsified if Egypt showed no capacity to absorb ideological crisis, with the Amarna period offered as a hypothetical example of a crisis that could have caused permanent collapse but did not. The target’s own mechanism explicitly claims Egypt successfully absorbed such disorder, so the forbidden case is a valid concrete observation that could realistically have obtained: had Egypt actually collapsed permanently after Amarna, the target’s mechanism would be undermined. The critic’s appeal to the Restoration Stela, damnatio memoriae, and Ramesside reconsolidation in fact confirms the target’s claim that Egypt did absorb the crisis, which is precisely why Egypt is excluded from the scope. The forbidden case remains a legitimate counterfactual test of the mechanism, not a straw man."}